---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
import Eyebrow from "../components/ui/Eyebrow.astro";
import RoadmapTimeline from "../components/RoadmapTimeline.astro";
import RoadmapForm from "../components/RoadmapForm.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Changelog · opchain"
  description="Release notes for opchain — what shipped, when, and how to migrate. Plus the live roadmap + community feature requests."
  active="/changelog"
>
  <main class="page">
    <div class="page-head">
      <Eyebrow>changelog</Eyebrow>
      <h1>Changelog.</h1>
    </div>

    <p class="lede">
      What shipped, when, and what to do about it. The skills are
      individual Markdown files; their <code>version</code> field is the
      source of truth — this page summarises across the catalog.
    </p>

    <!-- Live roadmap from Linear (build-time pull, label-gated).
         Sits above the release history so visitors see "what's coming"
         before "what's shipped". -->
    <RoadmapTimeline />

    <!-- Expanded detail for the upcoming releases (v1.5 next, then v1.6 /
         v1.7 planned). The roadmap cards above deep-link here (#v1-5 /
         #v1-6 / #v1-7) so a one-line card opens into the full theme
         writeup. Content tracks roadmap/07-v15-v16-v17. -->
    <div class="upcoming-head">
      <Eyebrow>what's coming</Eyebrow>
      <h2 class="rhh">Upcoming releases</h2>
    </div>

    <section class="release release--next" id="v1-5">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--next">v1.5</span>
        <h2>Build the AI app</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">next · built, awaiting release</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        v1.5 is opchain's next release &mdash; built and in the release
        pipeline, not yet live. It closes the biggest categorical gap in
        the catalog: nothing today owns <em>AI-feature</em> design. v1.5
        adds <strong>four new AI-native skills</strong> &mdash;
        <code>claude-api</code>, <code>rag-forge</code>,
        <code>agent-forge</code>, <code>prompt-ops</code> &mdash; wired
        through the existing pipeline, and lockstep-bumps the catalog from
        18 to <strong>22 skills</strong> at <code>1.5.0</code>. Markdown
        methodology turns out to be exactly the right shape for the things
        AI apps need most: source-controlled, diffable, version-pinned
        prompts and eval sets.
      </p>

      <h3>What's coming</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong><code>claude-api</code> &mdash; <code>/claude-api</code>.</strong>
          Model selection (Opus / Sonnet / Haiku routing), prompt caching
          as a default, batch vs. streaming, tool use, and
          <code>/claude-api migrate</code> playbooks for model-version
          bumps (4.6 → 4.7, retired-model replacement). Cache-audit checks
          hit rate; cost guardrails cap tokens per phase.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>rag-forge</code> &mdash; <code>/rag</code>.</strong>
          Tri-agent (Designer / Builder / Evaluator). Vector-DB decision
          tree, embedding-model choice, chunking strategy, hybrid search,
          and retrieval eval (<code>/rag eval</code>, <code>/rag bench</code>)
          with golden sets and recall@k / NDCG.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>agent-forge</code> &mdash; <code>/agent</code>.</strong>
          Tri-agent (Planner / Builder / Evaluator). Claude Agent SDK
          scaffold, subagent topology, tool-budget design, harness-loop
          shapes (chat / autonomous / human-in-the-loop), and an eval
          harness over golden trajectories.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>prompt-ops</code> &mdash; <code>/prompt</code>.</strong>
          Prompts as first-class artifacts: file-shaped versioning, eval
          datasets, and regression detection. <code>/prompt regress</code>
          runs the golden set on PR-changed prompts and blocks on a drop.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cross-skill ripples</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong><code>oc-app-architect</code></strong> gains an "AI app?"
          branch in <code>/discover</code> that routes to the four new
          skills.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>oc-stack-forge</code></strong> adds vector-DB packs
          (pgvector, Turbopuffer, Pinecone, Supabase Vectors) to the v1.4
          pack registry &mdash; pure additive.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>oc-code-auditor</code></strong> learns
          prompt-injection and tool-use safety rules.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Site &amp; GTM</h3>
      <p>
        New <a href="/ai-recipes">/ai-recipes</a> walkthroughs, a
        "Build AI apps" row on <a href="/compare">/compare</a>, an AI-app
        variant of <a href="/pipeline-builder">/pipeline-builder</a>, the
        <a href="/blog">/blog</a> dev-log scaffold with launch posts, a
        <a href="/for-agencies">/for-agencies</a> page, and the
        newsletter flag wired (Buttondown). The <a href="/demo">/demo</a>
        Worker is rewritten on <code>claude-api</code> patterns, and
        opchain's own eval set ships under <code>prompt-ops</code> as the
        dogfooding proof.
      </p>

      <h3>Compatibility</h3>
      <p>
        Back-compatible with v1.4. No migration steps required. All 22
        skills version-bump to <code>1.5.0</code> in lockstep (catalog tag
        <code>skills-v1.5.0</code>); the four new skills ship gated behind
        their <code>skills.registry.&lt;id&gt;.enabled</code> flags, so
        existing installs are unchanged until you opt in.
        <code>opchain-skills.zip</code> bundles everything as before.
      </p>

      <p class="planned-note">
        Built &mdash; shipping next, not yet live.
        <a href="#roadmap-vote">Vote on it above</a> to signal priority.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release release--next" id="v1-6">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--next">v1.6</span>
        <h2>The instrumented pipeline</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">planned · after v1.5 ships</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        v1.5 introduces four AI-native skills; the predictable next question is
        <em>what did they cost, and is my pipeline actually getting
        better?</em> v1.6 answers both. It adds cost attribution and opt-in
        telemetry, turns every skill's pass/fail into a graded eval score,
        and ships the first <code>oc-checkpoint-protocol</code> bump since
        v1.2.
      </p>

      <h3>New skills</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong><code>cost-ops</code> &mdash; <code>/cost</code>.</strong>
          Attributes Anthropic spend to each skill phase, adds budget gates
          to checkpoints, and recommends model-tier routing &mdash; Haiku
          for cheap repetitive phases, Opus for spec and audit. Finally
          answers "what did this feature cost to ship?"
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>telemetry-ops</code> &mdash; <code>/telemetry</code>.</strong>
          Opt-in, local-first usage metering written to
          <code>.checkpoints/usage.sqlite</code>. Aggregates anonymized
          "which skills people actually use" stats &mdash; the data behind
          the new public <code>/dashboard</code>. Nothing leaves your
          machine unless you opt in.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Cross-skill ripples</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong><code>oc-bug-check</code> + <code>oc-code-auditor</code></strong>
          stop emitting bare pass/fail and start scoring against a stable
          rubric.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>oc-monitoring-ops</code></strong> gains an "AI-app"
          template covering token rate, eval drift, and hallucination
          flags.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>prompt-ops</code></strong> (from v1.5) begins
          populating <code>cost_per_eval</code> and
          <code>eval_score_trend</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>oc-orchestrator</code></strong>'s <code>/ops next</code>
          factors cost and remaining budget into what it recommends you do
          next.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Protocol bump</h3>
      <p>
        <code>oc-checkpoint-protocol v1.3</code> &mdash; the first bump since
        the v1.2 PM-MCP fields &mdash; adds <code>cost</code>,
        <code>eval_scores</code>, and <code>telemetry_handle</code>.
        <code>oc-migration-ops</code> rolls it across every skill the same way
        the governance frontmatter rolled out in v1.4.
      </p>

      <h3>Site &amp; dogfood</h3>
      <p>
        A public <code>/dashboard</code> of anonymized aggregate usage, a
        <code>/showcase</code> finally backed by real cost-per-shipped-feature
        numbers from opchain's own pipeline, and a replays section with cost
        overlays on real runs. All 24 skills lockstep-bump to
        <code>1.6.0</code>.
      </p>

      <p class="planned-note">
        Planned &mdash; scope may shift before release.
        <a href="#roadmap-vote">Vote on the items above</a> to weigh in.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release release--next" id="v1-7">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--next">v1.7</span>
        <h2>Pick one distribution play</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">planned · lean: marketplace + templates</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        By the time v1.6 ships, opchain has 24 skills, instrumented
        pipelines, and AI-native coverage. The biggest remaining gap isn't
        features &mdash; it's <strong>distribution</strong>. v1.7
        deliberately promotes one growth play into a flagship theme instead
        of accreting more skills. The current lean is
        <strong>marketplace + templates</strong>.
      </p>

      <h3>The lean plan</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong><code>marketplace</code>.</strong> A site surface for
          community-contributed skills and packs. Every contribution adds
          breadth at zero core-team cost &mdash; and opchain itself becomes
          the first entry in its own marketplace.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>template-ops</code> &mdash; <code>/template</code>.</strong>
          Opinionated project starters that pre-wire an entire pipeline
          &mdash; stack, skills, and checkpoints &mdash; so a new project is
          ready to run from the first commit.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Why this lean: it compounds, and it's the natural follow-on once
        v1.6's telemetry exists to grade community contributions on real
        usage.
      </p>

      <h3>Alternatives on the table</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Agency play.</strong> <code>monorepo-ops</code> for real
          multi-project checkpoint scoping, a <code>/for-agencies</code>
          expansion, and a client-handoff demo scenario.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Pipeline depth.</strong> <code>discovery-ops</code>
          (JTBD / opportunity trees, upstream of <code>oc-app-architect</code>)
          plus <code>qa-ops</code> splitting test-pyramid design out of
          <code>oc-bug-check</code>.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>GTM</h3>
      <p>
        A marketplace launch post, a <code>/case-studies</code> page with
        named (or pseudonymous) builds, and a <code>/community</code> hub.
      </p>

      <p class="planned-note">
        Lean, not locked &mdash; the final v1.7 theme is chosen after the
        v1.5 / v1.6 retro.
      </p>
    </section>

    <RoadmapForm />

    <div class="release-history-head">
      <Eyebrow>release history</Eyebrow>
      <h2 class="rhh">What's already shipped</h2>
    </div>

    <section class="release release--current" id="v1-4">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag">v1.4</span>
        <h2>Coverage as a plugin registry</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-05-12</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        opchain v1.4 turns <code>oc-stack-forge</code>'s coverage from
        hardcoded prose into a versioned <strong>pack registry</strong> &mdash;
        one <code>pack.yml</code> per language, framework, mobile
        platform, or deploy target, validated on every build. Total
        coverage grows from 6 stacks in v1.3 to <strong>32 packs</strong>
        in v1.4: 13 languages, 9 frameworks, 4 mobile platforms, and 6
        deploy targets. Pack additions ship as one PR each &mdash; no
        more touching SKILL.md prose.
      </p>

      <h3>What's new</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>Pack registry architecture.</strong>
          <a href="/coverage">/coverage</a> is the user-visible catalog.
          <code>skills/oc-stack-forge/packs/&lt;id&gt;/pack.yml</code> is the
          source of truth; <code>scripts/gen-stack-packs.mjs</code> validates
          every pack on every build (bidirectional <code>language</code> ↔
          <code>frameworks</code> invariants, ref-doc budgets, etc.) and
          emits a coverage-flag per language / framework / mobile pack
          (deploy-targets are sub-selections, no flag).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Hybrid dispatch.</strong> <code>oc-deploy-ops</code> reads
          packs at runtime via <code>src/lib/pack-dispatch.js</code> for
          deploy-path lookup. <code>oc-api-dev</code> reads packs at
          build time via <code>scripts/gen-api-dev-adapters.mjs</code> to
          codegen typed per-language scaffold metadata. Two halves of one
          model: small-and-current vs. richer-and-typed.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>kind:mobile dispatch.</strong> Mobile packs render the
          ref doc as a <em>release checklist</em> via
          <code>dispatchMobile()</code> instead of executing commands.
          App Store + Play Store reviews are checklist-driven, not
          automated; the dispatcher pins that contract so no agent
          accidentally tries to <code>xcrun altool</code> its way to
          production.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Modern web bulk (PR 4).</strong> elixir / bun / deno
          language packs; phoenix / remix / sveltekit / solid framework
          packs. Bun and Deno are modelled as language packs because the
          toolchain diverges from Node's (
          <code>bun test</code>, <code>deno task build</code>).
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Enterprise bulk (PR 5).</strong> java / csharp / kotlin
          / php language packs; spring-java / dotnet-aspnet / spring-kotlin
          / laravel-php framework packs. <code>mvn checkstyle:check</code>,
          <code>dotnet format --verify-no-changes</code>, <code>ktlint</code>,
          <code>phpcs</code> wired as canonical lint commands.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Apple/iOS (PR 6).</strong> swift language pack + swiftui
          framework pack + ios-swiftui mobile pack + app-store deploy
          adapter. First production user of <code>dispatchMobile()</code>;
          the <code>ios-swiftui/mobile.md</code> reads as a usable
          App Store release checklist.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Mobile bulk (PR 6.5).</strong> kotlin-android / flutter /
          react-native-expo mobile packs + play-store deploy adapter.
          Flutter and React Native ship pinned to <code>play-store</code>
          as the sole deploy target; a follow-up will append
          <code>app-store</code> once the cross-platform supportedPlatforms
          ADR settles.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Hosting adapters (PR 7).</strong> railway / netlify /
          heroku / aws-amplify deploy-target packs. Sub-selections under
          existing language and framework packs; <code>getDispatchTarget()</code>
          picks the right provider section of <code>oc-deploy-ops</code>'s
          SKILL.md.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>The pipeline that shipped it</h3>
      <p>
        v1.4 went through opchain itself. <code>oc-app-architect</code>
        planned the eight-PR sequence. PRs 1-3 landed serially (architecture,
        backfill, dispatcher); PRs 4-7 ran in <em>parallel</em> from
        sibling worktrees on the same <code>origin/main</code> base,
        opened concurrently, and merged sequentially with rebases.
        <code>oc-release-ops</code> drafted this changelog entry from the
        merged PR summaries and bumped the 5 changed skills' SKILL.md
        versions atomically.
      </p>

      <h3>Compatibility</h3>
      <p>
        Back-compatible with v1.3. No migration steps required. Five
        skills version-bump <code>1.3.0</code> → <code>1.4.0</code> in
        lockstep: <code>oc-stack-forge</code>, <code>oc-api-dev</code>,
        <code>oc-deploy-ops</code>, <code>oc-app-architect</code>,
        <code>oc-migration-ops</code>. The other thirteen skills stay on
        <code>1.3.0</code>. <code>opchain-skills.zip</code> ships
        bundle-everything as before; the <code>skills.coverage.*</code>
        flags filter what <code>oc-stack-forge</code> offers, not what gets
        downloaded.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--past">v1.3</span>
        <h2>Runtime PM, real platforms, automated releases</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-05-11</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        opchain v1.3 makes the v1.2 PM-MCP prose executable end-to-end,
        expands the platform menu beyond JS / Cloudflare, and ships
        <code>oc-release-ops</code> — the 18th skill — to automate the
        "scope → /changelog → bump → ship" cadence opchain uses for itself.
      </p>

      <h3>What's new</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>The PM-MCP loop is real.</strong> v1.2 taught the skills to
          <em>describe</em> PM-tool calls; v1.3 actually invokes them. A
          concrete tool-name registry, retry / backoff, idempotency markers,
          and a deferred-action queue mean the four PM-aware skills
          (<code>oc-app-architect</code>, <code>oc-git-ops</code>,
          <code>oc-deploy-ops</code>, <code>oc-monitoring-ops</code>) can crash-restart
          mid-flow without polluting Linear / Jira / GitHub Issues.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong><code>oc-release-ops</code> is the 18th skill.</strong> Verbs:
          <code>/release plan|draft|bump|announce|ship</code>. Reads every
          skill's checkpoint to propose the next semver, drafts the changelog
          entry from sprint outputs, atomically bumps all skill versions,
          opens a release ticket via PM-MCP, hands off to <code>oc-git-ops</code>
          for the merge and <code>oc-deploy-ops</code> for staging + prod.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Platform menu grew.</strong> Django + Postgres + Render,
          Rails + Postgres + Heroku, Go + Fly.io, and Rust + Axum +
          Shuttle.rs are first-class in <code>oc-stack-forge</code>'s decision
          tree, <code>oc-app-architect</code>'s scaffold recipes, and
          <code>oc-deploy-ops</code>'s provider sections.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Build-time PM-MCP validator.</strong>
          <code>scripts/validate-pm-mcp.mjs</code> runs in <code>npm run prebuild</code>
          and CI; blocks the build on placeholder drift, missing protocol
          citations, or unknown tool names.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Three new scenarios</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#runtime-pm-loop">Ticket → ship → incident → postmortem on one Linear thread</a>
          — the v1.3 hero. Six skills, one Linear thread, runtime PM-MCP
          end-to-end with a transient 503 mid-deploy that the deferred-action
          queue handles cleanly.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#release-ops-dogfood">oc-release-ops ships its own release</a>
          — opchain v1.3.0 shipped via opchain v1.3.0. Meta proof that the
          new skill works for any opchain-managed project.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#django-render-shipped">Django + Postgres + Render, shipped by opchain</a>
          — solo founder, GitHub Issues for tracking, Render Blueprint for
          deploy. Same opchain pipeline, no Cloudflare in sight.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Configuration</h3>
      <p>
        v1.3 adds <code>tool_overrides</code> to <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code>
        for brokered / regulated MCP environments and an
        <code>extended</code> map under <code>states</code> for deploy /
        incident workflow names. See the
        <a href="/demo#runtime-pm-loop">runtime-pm-loop scenario</a> for the
        full schema.
      </p>

      <h3>Compatibility</h3>
      <p>
        Back-compatible with v1.2. No migration steps required. The new
        validator's first run will fail-closed if any of the five PM-aware
        SKILL.md files still carry the legacy
        <code>mcp.&lt;provider&gt;.&lt;verb&gt;</code> placeholder; if you
        forked v1.2 prose, search-replace those before upgrading. Every skill
        version is in lockstep at <code>1.3.0</code>.
      </p>

      <h3>Security posture</h3>
      <p>
        The runtime PM loop is enrichment, not load-bearing — every PM-aware
        verb still completes its primary job (sprint plan / commit / deploy /
        incident open) when the MCP server is unreachable. In regulated
        environments (HIPAA / FedRAMP / CMMC), set <code>tool_overrides</code>
        in <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code> to point each operation at the
        broker / redactor / audit-pipeline that fronts your Linear or Jira
        tenant. The <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-f500">F500 healthcare</a>
        and <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-defense">defense CMMC L3</a>
        scenarios from v1.2 remain the reference architectures.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--past">v1.2</span>
        <h2>PM-tool MCP integration</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-05-05</span>
      </header>

      <p class="rel-summary">
        opchain v1.2 wires the skills into the PM-tool MCPs Anthropic
        ships with Claude Code. Linear, Jira, and GitHub Issues become
        first-class context for <code>oc-app-architect</code>, <code>oc-git-ops</code>,
        <code>oc-deploy-ops</code>, and <code>oc-monitoring-ops</code> — the
        ticket is the thread of execution, not a side artefact.
      </p>

      <h3>What's new</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>oc-app-architect /discover</strong> accepts a ticket
          reference and pre-fills the interview from the ticket body +
          comments. <code>/roadmap</code> writes the sprint plan back as
          a structured comment and (optionally) creates a child ticket
          per sprint.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>oc-git-ops /git-sync TICKET-1234</strong> reads the
          ticket, shapes the branch / commit / PR from it, and
          transitions ticket state on PR open and merge. The PR body
          is generated from ticket description, diff summary, and
          auditor + oc-bug-check output.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>oc-code-auditor</strong> findings post back to the
          linked PM ticket, not just the checkpoint.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>oc-deploy-ops</strong> auto-creates a deploy ticket per
          environment, parent-linked to every commit's tickets.
          Transitions the deploy ticket through
          <em>in-progress → staging-verified → shipped</em>
          (or <em>rolled-back</em>); comments back on each linked
          ticket on prod ship.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>oc-monitoring-ops</strong> opens an incident ticket
          when alerts fire, parent-linked to the most recent deploy
          ticket. Auto-creates remediation sub-tickets when the
          postmortem publishes.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>oc-integrations-engineer</strong> is the canonical
          owner of the PM-MCP integration patterns; its SKILL.md
          documents detection, scoping, and audit-pipeline
          expectations for regulated environments.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Two new scenarios</h3>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-f500">MCP at a Fortune-500 healthcare insurer</a>
          — HIPAA + ISO 27001 + SOC2 + an internal AI-Use Policy;
          custom PHI-redacting FHIR proxy MCP; SIEM-forwarded audit
          log; phased rollout with abort criteria.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#mcp-enterprise-defense">MCP at a CMMC L3 defense prime</a>
          — FedRAMP High / IL5; on-prem MCP fleet; PIV/CAC-rooted
          broker; cross-domain Guard signatures for the MCP envelope;
          ATO modification package and STIG-hardened workstation
          profile.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="/demo#pm-pipeline-linear">v1.2 hero scenario — Linear-led pipeline</a>
          — the full v1.2 flow on a real Linear ticket, ticket → ship
          → first incident, with Jira and GitHub Issues called out
          as one-line config swaps.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h3>Configuration</h3>
      <p>
        v1.2 adds <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code> at the repo root.
        Default mapping is Linear; Jira and GitHub Issues are drop-in
        with provider-specific issue-type and state mappings. See the
        <a href="/demo#pm-pipeline-linear">hero scenario</a> for the
        full schema.
      </p>

      <h3>Compatibility</h3>
      <p>
        v1.2 is backward-compatible with v1.1. Without a
        <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code> file (or with an MCP server
        unconfigured) every skill operates as it did in v1.1; the PM
        loop is enrichment, never a hard dependency. Skills will
        prompt once on first use to write the config, then proceed.
      </p>

      <h3>Security posture</h3>
      <p>
        Regulated environments should not adopt v1.2 by default. The
        Fortune-500 and Defense scenarios document the broker /
        redactor / audit-pipeline / cross-domain rules that must
        precede any production deployment under HIPAA, FedRAMP,
        CMMC, ITAR, or equivalent regimes. v1.2 is opt-in via
        <code>.opchain/pm.yaml</code>; the regulated scenarios are
        the reference architectures for adopting it safely.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--past">v1.1</span>
        <h2>Stable release</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-04</span>
      </header>
      <p class="rel-summary">
        Tri-agent harness across <code>oc-app-architect</code>,
        <code>oc-code-auditor</code>, <code>oc-integrations-engineer</code>;
        full-pipeline flow from <code>/discover</code> to
        <code>/deploy</code>; oc-checkpoint-protocol v1.0 across every
        skill; static Astro site; first set of six in-action
        scenarios.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="release">
      <header class="rel-head">
        <span class="rel-tag rel-tag--past">v1.0</span>
        <h2>Initial release</h2>
        <span class="rel-date">2026-02</span>
      </header>
      <p class="rel-summary">
        First public cut of the opchain skill catalog as a set of
        Markdown files installable into Claude Code. No site, no
        scenarios; just the skills.
      </p>
    </section>

    <p class="footer-note">
      Skill versions are stamped in <code>skills/&lt;name&gt;/SKILL.md</code>
      under <code>version:</code>; this page rolls them up by feature.
    </p>
  </main>
</Base>

